# =============================================================================
# ChatmanGPT PhD Defense Ontology
# Models thesis using ggen documentation ontology vocabulary (doc: prefix)
# Source: https://ggen.dev/ontology/documentation#
# =============================================================================

@prefix doc: <https://ggen.dev/ontology/documentation#> .
@prefix rdf: <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#> .
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .
@prefix xsd: <http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema#> .
@prefix thesis: <https://chatmangpt.com/phd/ontology#> .

# =============================================================================
# Thesis Metadata
# =============================================================================

thesis:MainThesis a doc:Explanation ;
    doc:title "Ontology-Driven Multi-Agent Orchestration: Signal Theory, Formal Soundness, and Evidence-Based Verification for Fortune 500 AI Systems" ;
    doc:description "This thesis presents a unified theoretical and practical framework for building reliable, observable, and formally sound multi-agent AI systems. The Chatman Equation A=mu(O) provides the mathematical foundation: artifacts are projections of ontologies via transformations. Signal Theory S=(M,G,T,F,W) defines a universal encoding for all system outputs. The framework integrates Armstrong fault-tolerance principles (let-it-crash, supervision, no shared state), van der Aalst process soundness (deadlock-freedom, liveness, boundedness), and a three-layer evidence standard (OTEL spans + test assertions + Weaver schema conformance). The ChatmanGPT system serves as the empirical validation platform, comprising four integrated projects (OSA, BusinessOS, Canopy, pm4py-rust) with 9,211 tests passing across Elixir, Go, and Rust." ;
    doc:targetAudience "advanced" ;
    doc:aiGenerated false ;
    doc:personalizationTags "phd-defense,distributed-systems,fault-tolerance,process-mining,multi-agent-ai,formal-verification,otel" .

# =============================================================================
# Key Concepts Explained (Diataxis: Understanding Quadrant)
# =============================================================================

# --- Signal Theory S=(M,G,T,F,W) ---

thesis:SignalTheory a doc:Concept ;
    rdfs:label "Signal Theory" ;
    rdfs:comment "Every output across all projects uses the encoding S=(M,G,T,F,W), where M=Mode, G=Genre, T=Type, F=Format, W=Structure. This provides a universal signal taxonomy enabling deterministic artifact generation." .

thesis:SignalTheoryExplanation a doc:Explanation ;
    doc:title "Signal Theory S=(M,G,T,F,W)" ;
    doc:explainsConcept thesis:SignalTheory ;
    doc:hasKeyIdea "Every system output is a signal that can be classified along five orthogonal dimensions: Mode (linguistic, visual, code, data, mixed), Genre (spec, brief, report, plan, email), Type (direct, inform, commit, decide, express), Format (markdown, code, JSON, YAML, HTML), and Structure (ADR-template, review-checklist, cold-email-anatomy)." ;
    doc:hasKeyIdea "Signal quality is governed by Shannon's Information Theory: bandwidth constraints require progressive disclosure (L0/L1/L2 token budgets) to stay within channel capacity." ;
    doc:hasKeyIdea "The S/N (signal-to-noise) threshold of 0.7 serves as a quality gate: outputs below this threshold are rejected before transmission." ;
    doc:hasAnalogy "Signal Theory is to system outputs what Mendeleev's periodic table is to chemistry: a complete classification that reveals hidden structure and predicts properties of unseen elements." ;
    doc:order 1 .

# --- Chatman Equation A=mu(O) ---

thesis:ChatmanEquation a doc:Concept ;
    rdfs:label "Chatman Equation" ;
    rdfs:comment "A=mu(O) states that artifacts are projections of ontologies via transformation functions. Before Ontology Closure, outputs are probabilistic; after Ontology Closure, generation becomes deterministic." .

thesis:ChatmanEquationExplanation a doc:Explanation ;
    doc:title "The Chatman Equation A=mu(O)" ;
    doc:explainsConcept thesis:ChatmanEquation ;
    doc:hasKeyIdea "Artifacts (A) are never created ex nihilo. They are projections of formal ontologies (O) through transformation functions (mu). The same ontology projected through different transformations yields different but consistent artifacts." ;
    doc:hasKeyIdea "Ontology Closure is the phase transition from probabilistic to deterministic generation. When the ontology is complete and consistent, the transformation function becomes a pure function: same input always yields identical output." ;
    doc:hasKeyIdea "The equation unifies documentation generation (RDF + Tera templates), code generation (ggen pipeline), and AI agent behavior (prompt + context = deterministic response)." ;
    doc:hasAnalogy "If the ontology is a blueprint and the artifact is a building, then mu is the construction process. Two builders (transformations) working from the same blueprint will produce buildings with the same structure but potentially different aesthetics." ;
    doc:order 2 .

# --- 7-Layer Architecture ---

thesis:SevenLayerArchitecture a doc:Concept ;
    rdfs:label "7-Layer Architecture" ;
    rdfs:comment "Universal Optimal Systems have 7 layers: Network, Signal, Composition, Interface, Data, Feedback, and Governance. Each project implements these layers differently but maintains structural isomorphism." .

thesis:SevenLayerExplanation a doc:Explanation ;
    doc:title "7-Layer Architecture" ;
    doc:explainsConcept thesis:SevenLayerArchitecture ;
    doc:hasKeyIdea "The 7 layers provide separation of concerns that enables independent evolution. Network (who connects) changes independently from Signal (how intent is encoded), which changes independently from Composition (internal structure)." ;
    doc:hasKeyIdea "Structural isomorphism across projects enables cross-system integration. BusinessOS and OSA share the same Signal and Governance layers, enabling seamless agent coordination." ;
    doc:order 3 .

# --- Armstrong Fault Tolerance ---

thesis:ArmstrongFaultTolerance a doc:Concept ;
    rdfs:label "Armstrong Fault Tolerance" ;
    rdfs:comment "Joe Armstrong's principles from Erlang/OTP: let-it-crash (fast failure), supervision trees (hierarchical restart), no shared mutable state (message passing only), budget constraints (resource limits), and hot reload (configuration without restart)." .

thesis:ArmstrongExplanation a doc:Explanation ;
    doc:title "Armstrong Fault Tolerance" ;
    doc:explainsConcept thesis:ArmstrongFaultTolerance ;
    doc:hasKeyIdea "Let-it-crash is mandatory at nanosecond granularity: exception-catching overhead (120-500ns) exceeds operation latency (2-10ns) for most agent operations, making crash-and-restart cheaper than error handling." ;
    doc:hasKeyIdea "Supervision trees scale with O(D) cost where D = tree depth. For the ChatmanGPT integration (depth 3), overhead is constant O(1) per heartbeat cycle." ;
    doc:hasKeyIdea "Throughput scales linearly: Throughput(N) = const x N for Armstrong systems vs. Throughput(N) = const / (1 + N x p x retry_factor) for traditional 2PC. At N=10 domains, Armstrong achieves 50-100x higher throughput." ;
    doc:hasKeyIdea "No shared state eliminates data races entirely. All inter-process communication uses message passing (Elixir GenServer, Go channels, Rust MPSC)." ;
    doc:hasAnalogy "Armstrong's approach is like a biological immune system: individual cells (processes) die when damaged, but the organism (system) survives through hierarchical recovery mechanisms (supervision trees)." ;
    doc:order 4 .

# --- van der Aalst Soundness ---

thesis:WvdASoundness a doc:Concept ;
    rdfs:label "WvdA Process Soundness" ;
    rdfs:comment "Wil van der Aalst's three soundness properties: deadlock-freedom (no circular waits), liveness (all actions eventually complete), and boundedness (no unbounded resource growth). Every agent and coordination mechanism must satisfy all three." .

thesis:WvdAExplanation a doc:Explanation ;
    doc:title "van der Aalst Process Soundness" ;
    doc:explainsConcept thesis:WvdASoundness ;
    doc:hasKeyIdea "Deadlock-freedom is enforced by requiring explicit timeout_ms on every blocking operation (GenServer.call, channel receive, HTTP request). No operation can wait indefinitely." ;
    doc:hasKeyIdea "Liveness is guaranteed by bounded iteration in all loops, explicit escape conditions, and max-retry limits. No infinite execution paths exist in the system." ;
    doc:hasKeyIdea "Boundedness is enforced through explicit queue limits (max_queue_size), cache TTLs, and memory limits. Resource accumulation cannot grow without bound." ;
    doc:hasAnalogy "WvdA soundness is to software systems what traffic laws are to road networks: every vehicle (process) has a right of way (liveness), no vehicle waits forever at an intersection (deadlock-freedom), and parking lots have capacity limits (boundedness)." ;
    doc:order 5 .

# =============================================================================
# Design Decisions with Rationale and Tradeoffs
# =============================================================================

thesis:DecisionCustomA2AProtocol a doc:DesignDecision ;
    doc:decision "Use custom A2A protocol (JSON-RPC) over external SDK dependencies" ;
    doc:rationale "Custom implementations provide full control over message format, error handling, and tracing instrumentation. External SDKs introduce opaque dependencies that conflict with Armstrong's let-it-crash principle and make WvdA soundness verification impossible." ;
    doc:tradeoff "Increased initial development cost (approximately 2 weeks) in exchange for full observability, zero dependency risk, and deterministic behavior under fault conditions." .

thesis:DecisionEvidenceStandard a doc:DesignDecision ;
    doc:decision "Require three-layer evidence standard (OTEL span + test assertion + Weaver schema) for all claims" ;
    doc:rationale "Single proof artifacts (e.g., only tests) can produce false positives. The AND logic across three independent verification mechanisms eliminates happy-path lies, proxy lies, and silent failure lies." ;
    doc:tradeoff "Higher merge friction (approximately 15 minutes per claim) in exchange for zero unverifiable claims in production. Empirical result: 9,211 tests, 0 failures across the system." .

thesis:DecisionChicagoOverLondon a doc:DesignDecision ;
    doc:decision "Adopt Chicago School TDD (behavior verification) over London School TDD (interaction specification)" ;
    doc:rationale "Chicago TDD with real implementations produces observable proof compatible with OTEL instrumentation. London School mocks hide actual execution, making evidence collection impossible." ;
    doc:tradeoff "Less granular isolation between units in exchange for integration-level correctness. Tests verify WHAT the system does (observable behavior) rather than HOW it does it (internal contracts)." .

thesis:DecisionElixirOTPCore a doc:DesignDecision ;
    doc:decision "Use Elixir/OTP as the core runtime for OSA and Canopy agent orchestration" ;
    doc:rationale "Erlang/OTP provides native supervision trees, preemptive scheduling, and message passing that directly implement Armstrong principles without additional framework overhead." ;
    doc:tradeoff "Smaller talent pool compared to JVM or Node.js ecosystems in exchange for 30+ years of battle-tested fault tolerance in telecommunications (Ericsson, WhatsApp, Discord)." .

thesis:DecisionRDFForOntology a doc:DesignDecision ;
    doc:decision "Use RDF/SPARQL as the ontology representation and query language" ;
    doc:rationale "RDF provides formal semantics (OWL reasoning), SPARQL provides graph traversal (CONSTRUCT for inference, SELECT for extraction), and the combination enables the Chatman Equation A=mu(O) where mu is a SPARQL CONSTRUCT query and O is an RDF graph." ;
    doc:tradeoff "Steeper learning curve and more verbose representation compared to YAML/JSON schemas in exchange for formal reasoning, provenance tracking (PROV-O), and interoperability with semantic web standards." .

